al, including never before seen documents, and extensive interviews with Tibetans, including the Dalai Lama, and with Chinese officials. Goldstein furnishes fascinating and sometimes surprising portraits of these major players as he deftly unravels the fateful intertwining of Tibetan and Chinese politics against the backdrop of the Korean War, the tenuous Sino-Soviet alliance, and American cold war policy.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 7aHISTORY / Asia / General.2bisacsh  a1950s.  aarchival.  abeijing.  achinese communists.  achinese government.  achinese history.  achinese politics.  acold war.  acommunist party.  acontemporary.  adalai lama.  aillustrated.  ainterviews.  akorean war.  amidcentury.  amodern world.  apeoples liberation army.  apolitical.  apolitics.  apublic policy.  asino soviet alliance.  asocioeconomic reform.  atibet.  atibetan history.  avolume 2.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013z97831106904220 cprintz978052024941740uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052093332340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520933323423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520933323/original  a978-3-11-069042-2  University of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_FAO  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-UCY